Part 1: The Big Picture — How Everything Works Together

Before diving into the details, let me explain the simple logic behind everything you set up this morning. Think of your blog like a restaurant:

VS Code Your kitchen. This is where you write, edit and create everything. Nobody else sees this.	
GitHub Your storage & delivery. It stores your files and sends them to the internet automatically.	
huyenvi.blog Your restaurant front. This is what visitors see when they come to your website.

The flow is always the same: You write in VS Code → You push to GitHub → GitHub updates your live website automatically. That is the entire logic!


Part 2: Visual Studio Code — Your Writing & Design Tool

VS Code (Visual Studio Code) is a free program made by Microsoft. It is like a very smart text editor — similar to Microsoft Word, but designed for building websites and writing code.

What VS Code does for your blog
•	It lets you write and edit your blog posts
•	It lets you change the design and colours of your site
•	It lets you organise all your files in one place
•	It has a built-in Terminal so you can run commands without switching apps

How VS Code connects to your website
VS Code itself does NOT connect directly to your website. Think of it like this:

The simple chain:
VS Code (you edit files here) → Terminal (you run 3 commands) → GitHub (receives your files) → huyenvi.blog (the world sees it)

VS Code is just the place where you make changes. The Terminal (the black command window) is what actually sends your work to GitHub.

💡 Good to know
You can open Terminal directly inside VS Code by pressing Ctrl + ` (the key above Tab on the left). This means you never have to leave VS Code!


Part 3: GitHub — Your Storage & Publisher

GitHub is a free service on the internet that stores your website files. When you send your files to GitHub, it automatically builds and publishes your website for the world to see.

Why do we need GitHub?
•	It stores all your files safely in the cloud
•	It automatically turns your files into a live website
•	It keeps a history of every change you ever make (so you can undo mistakes)
•	It gives you a free web address (huyentrang060996-glitch.github.io)
•	It works with your custom domain huyenvi.blog

The 3 commands you run every time
Every time you want your changes to go live, you run these 3 commands in Terminal. Think of them like packing and shipping a box:

1	git add .
"Pack up all the changes I made" — this collects everything you edited or created
2	git commit -m "description"
"Label the package" — write a short note about what you changed (e.g. new post, fix header)
3	git push ...
"Send the package to GitHub" — this uploads everything and your live website updates in 2 minutes


Part 4: Your Blog Folder — What Every File Does

When you open VS Code and see the MY-BLOG folder on the left side, here is what every folder and file means:

Folder / File	What it does
_posts/	This is where ALL your blog posts live. Every time you write something new, you create a new file here. This is the folder you will use most often.
_layouts/	This contains the HTML skeleton of your pages. The file default.html controls what appears on every single page — the header, navigation, and overall structure.
_includes/	This contains small reusable pieces of HTML (like a header or footer) that you can insert into multiple pages. You will rarely need to touch this.
assets/css/	This is where your design lives. The file style.css controls all the visual things — colours, fonts, spacing, and layout of your entire site.
_config.yml	This is the master settings file for your whole site. It contains your site title, email, website URL, and other global settings. After editing this file, you must restart the server.
index.markdown	This is your homepage — what people see first when they visit huyenvi.blog. You can edit this to change your intro text and what appears on the home page.
about.markdown	This is your About page. Write about yourself, your story, and what your blog is about.
now.markdown	This is your Now page (like Steph Ango's). Tell readers what you are currently reading, watching, doing.
Gemfile	This is a list of software packages your blog needs to run. You will almost never need to edit this file.
CNAME	This tiny file tells GitHub what your custom domain is (huyenvi.blog). Do not edit or delete this file.


Part 5: How to Write and Publish a New Post

This is your most important daily workflow. Follow these steps every time you want to publish something new.

Step 1 — Create the post file
In VS Code, right-click on the _posts/ folder and choose New File. Name it in this exact format:

File naming rule:
YEAR-MONTH-DAY-title-of-your-post.markdown  Example: 2026-04-27-my-trip-to-hoi-an.markdown

Step 2 — Add the front matter
Every post must start with these lines at the very top. This tells Jekyll the title, date and layout of your post:

---
layout: default
title: "My trip to Hoi An"
date: 2026-04-27
---
Write your post content here...

Step 3 — Write your content using Markdown
Markdown is a simple way of writing that automatically turns into beautiful HTML. Here are the basics:

What you type	What it becomes
# Big Title	A large heading at the top
## Smaller Title	A medium sized section heading
**bold text**	Bold text
*italic text*	Italic text
[Click here](https://...)	A clickable link
![Photo description](/assets/images/photo.jpg)	An image in your post
- Item one	A bullet point list item

Step 4 — Save and publish

1	Save the file in VS Code
Press ⌘ Cmd + S to save your post file
2	Open Terminal
Press Ctrl + ` inside VS Code, or open the Terminal app
3	Run the 3 git commands
git add .   then   git commit -m "new post"   then   git push ...
4	Wait 2 minutes
GitHub builds and publishes your site automatically
5	Refresh huyenvi.blog
Your post is now live for the whole world to read!


Part 6: How to Add a Photo to a Post

1	Copy your photo into the assets/images/ folder
In VS Code, drag and drop your photo file into the assets/images/ folder on the left sidebar
2	Add this line in your post where you want the photo to appear
![Description of photo](/assets/images/your-photo-name.jpg)
3	Save, then push to GitHub with the 3 commands
Your photo will appear in the post on your live site


Part 7: How to Change the Design of Your Website

Your site design is controlled by two files. Here is which file to edit depending on what you want to change:

What you want to change	Which file to edit
Colours, fonts, spacing, sizes	assets/css/style.css
Add or remove nav links (About, Now)	_layouts/default.html
Change the site title or description	_config.yml  (then restart server)
Change your homepage text	index.markdown
Change your About page	about.markdown
Change your Now page	now.markdown

💡 Important reminder
After making any design change, always remember to save the file (⌘ Cmd + S) and then run the 3 git commands to push your changes to GitHub. Changes only go live after you push!


